    The error "Invalid shift exponent" occurs in the file program.c at line 9   
    within the function high_bit_mask:                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     9: return (unsigned long long)(1 << width);                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Analysis of the Error                                                       
                                                                                
     1 The Integer Literal: The literal 1 in C, by default, is of type int,     
       which is typically 32 bits on most modern architectures.                 
     2 The Shift Operation: The expression (1 << width) attempts to shift an    
       int left by width bits.                                                  
     3 The State: In main, width is set to 64.                                  
     4 Undefined Behavior: Shifting a 32-bit int by 64 bits invokes undefined   
       behavior. According to the C standard, the result of a shift expression  
       is undefined if the right-hand operand (the shift count) is greater      
       than or equal to the width of the promoted left-hand operand.            
                                                                                
    Even though the result of the shift is cast to an unsigned long long        
    (which is typically 64 bits), the cast happens after the evaluation of 1    
    << width. Because the shift operation itself is performed on an int, the    
    overflow/undefined behavior occurs before the result is widened to a        
    64-bit type.                                                                
                                                                                
    Root Cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    The root cause is that the literal 1 is treated as a 32-bit int,            
    attempting to perform a bitwise shift greater than the capacity of the      
    type before the type conversion to unsigned long long takes place.          
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Minimal Local Fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Change the literal 1 to 1ULL (an unsigned long long literal). This ensures  
    the shift operation is performed on a 64-bit value, which is capable of     
    handling a shift of 64 bits (though note that shifting by 64 is still       
    technically undefined behavior on many platforms; you should handle width   
    == 64 as a special case if 2^64 is intended).                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Using 1ULL to promote to 64-bit before shifting                         
     return (1ULL << width);                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Note: Be aware that if width is precisely 64, even 1ULL << 64 is undefined  
    in C. You should add a check:                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static unsigned long long high_bit_mask(int width)                         
     {                                                                          
         if (width >= 64) {                                                     
             // Handle appropriately (e.g., return 0 or a max value)            
             return 0;                                                          
         }                                                                      
         return (1ULL << width);                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
